# User roles and access control

This project uses **8 fixed roles**. Roles cannot be created, deleted, or renamed at runtime; they live in `database/seeders/RolesSeeder.php`.

Every user has **exactly one role** (`users.role_id`) and an `is_active` flag (`users.is_active`).

This rule and the seeder/code MUST be kept in sync. When you change anything below, update all three:

1. This file (descriptions + access matrix).
2. `database/seeders/RolesSeeder.php` (descriptions only).
3. `app/Support/Access.php` (the `FEATURES` map for behaviour).
4. Create a new sync migration named `YYYY_MM_DD_HHMMSS_sync_role_descriptions.php` (or similar) that calls `(new RolesSeeder)->run()`. The seeder is idempotent (`updateOrCreate` keyed on `slug`).

## Roles

| Slug | Name | Scope |
|------|------|-------|
| `super_admin` | Super Admin | Full unrestricted access to the entire system. Only super admins can create, edit, deactivate, or delete other super admins, and only super admins can promote a user to super admin. The master user (`stistoyanov@yahoo.com`, defined in `Database\Seeders\MasterUserSeeder::EMAIL`) cannot be demoted, deactivated, or deleted. |
| `admin` | Admin | Full admin dashboard access for day-to-day operations. Cannot see, create, edit, deactivate, or delete super admin users. Cannot promote anyone to super admin. |
| `manager` | Manager | Oversees teams and content. No system pages yet — currently sees only Overview in the admin dashboard. |
| `user` | User | Standard authenticated user. Sees only Overview in the dashboard; everything else is system-only. |
| `viewer` | Viewer | Read-only auditor. Can view scheduler runs and Laravel logs but cannot clear or modify them. |
| `service_account` | Service Account | Non-human account used by external applications and APIs. **Cannot log in to the dashboard** — rejected in `LoginController`. |
| `operator` | Operator | Operational tasks: scheduler, logs, queues. Can clear logs and schedule-run history. Cannot manage users or system configuration. |
| `support` | Support | Assists end-users. Currently sees only Overview; future read-only user lookup is planned. |

## Access matrix

| Page / Action | Allowed roles |
|---------------|---------------|
| Login to dashboard | all except `service_account` |
| Overview (`/dashboard`) | every role that can log in |
| Overview heartbeat stats | `super_admin`, `admin`, `viewer`, `operator` |
| Files — view own (`/dashboard/files`) | every role that can log in |
| Files — upload | every role that can log in |
| Files — share / revoke own download link | file owner only |
| Files — download own | file owner |
| Files — view / download / delete others' files | `super_admin` (any), `admin` (no super admin owners) |
| Files — public download (`/files/d/{token}`) | anyone with the link (no auth) |
| Files — total storage cap | hard 100 GB across all uploads (enforced server-side) |
| Scheduler — view (`/dashboard/scheduler`) | `super_admin`, `admin`, `viewer`, `operator` |
| Scheduler — clear all | `super_admin`, `admin`, `operator` |
| Logs — view (`/dashboard/logs`) | `super_admin`, `admin`, `viewer`, `operator` |
| Logs — clear file | `super_admin`, `admin`, `operator` |
| Email test (`/dashboard/email`) | `super_admin`, `admin` |
| Users — view (`/dashboard/users`) | `super_admin` (sees all), `admin` (super admins hidden) |
| Users — create | `super_admin` (any role), `admin` (cannot assign `super_admin`) |
| Users — update / delete / toggle active | `super_admin` (any user), `admin` (no super admin targets) |
| Roles tab (`/dashboard/users/roles`) | `super_admin` (all roles visible), `admin` (super admin row hidden) |

The source of truth in code is `App\Support\Access::FEATURES`. Each entry maps a `feature` slug to a list of role slugs.

## When you add a new feature

Always do every step below:

1. **Decide which roles get access** before writing code, and state it in your PR/commit message.
2. Add a new entry to `App\Support\Access::FEATURES` keyed by a stable feature slug (e.g. `'reports.view' => ['super_admin', 'admin']`).
3. Protect every route with the `role` middleware using the same role list:
   ```php
   Route::get('/dashboard/reports', ...)->middleware('role:super_admin,admin');
   ```
4. Gate the sidebar/menu link with the `Access` helper:
   ```blade
   @if (App\Support\Access::allowed(auth()->user(), 'reports.view'))
       <a href="{{ route('dashboard.reports') }}">Reports</a>
   @endif
   ```
5. If the feature shows lists of users, mirror the `UserController` filtering pattern: when the current user is not a super admin, exclude super-admin records from queries and disallow actions on them.
6. Add a new row to the **Access matrix** in this file.
7. If you change a role description, also update `RolesSeeder` and add a new sync migration.
8. Test by logging in with at least one role inside and one role outside the allow-list.

## Behavioural rules (always enforced)

- Inactive users (`is_active = false`) cannot log in (`LoginController`) and cannot pass `role` middleware.
- Service accounts cannot log in to the dashboard at all.
- The master user cannot be demoted from `super_admin`, deactivated, or deleted.
- The currently-authenticated user is never listed in the Users tab and cannot modify themselves there.
- Admin users cannot see, list, query, or modify super admin users. Enforce in the controller queries, not just in the view.
- Hiding a UI element is not enough — every protected route MUST have the matching `role` middleware as a backstop.

## File map

| Concern | File |
|---------|------|
| Role list + descriptions | `database/seeders/RolesSeeder.php` |
| Access map (feature → roles) | `app/Support/Access.php` |
| Route guard | `app/Http/Middleware/EnsureRole.php` (alias `role`) |
| User role helpers | `app/Models/User.php` (`hasAnyRole`, `canAccess`, `isSuperAdmin`, `isMaster`) |
| Master user definition | `database/seeders/MasterUserSeeder.php` |
| Sync after description change | new migration calling `RolesSeeder::run()` |
| Files feature (model, controller, public download) | `app/Models/UploadedFile.php`, `app/Http/Controllers/FileController.php`, `app/Http/Controllers/PublicFileDownloadController.php` |
